               <p>JOHN CLARK. I am the <rs id="t18250915-367-viclabel2001" type="occupation">mate of a vessel called The Times</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18250915-367-victim1854 t18250915-367-viclabel2001"></join>, which lay opposite the <placeName id="t18250915-367-crimeloc2002">Custom-house</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18250915-367-crimeloc2002" type="placeName" value="Custom-house"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18250915-367-crimeloc2002" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18250915-367-off1999 t18250915-367-crimeloc2002"></join>, in the same tier with the Sarah and Mary - it is called the <placeName id="t18250915-367-crimeloc2003">Yarmouth tier</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18250915-367-crimeloc2003" type="placeName" value="Yarmouth tier"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18250915-367-crimeloc2003" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18250915-367-off1999 t18250915-367-crimeloc2003"></join>. When I went to bed on Saturday night, the 27th of July, I put my watch, seal, and key by the side of my bed. I awoke about six o'clock next morning, they were gone.</p>
               <p>(Property produced and sworn to.)</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18250915-367-person1855">
                  DANIEL 
                  BLIGH
               <interp inst="t18250915-367-person1855" type="surname" value="BLIGH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18250915-367-person1855" type="given" value="DANIEL"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18250915-367-person1855" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a Thames Police Surveyor. I was on duty about two o'clock in the morning of the 28th of August, and heard a call for the police from the Sarah and Mary. I went on board, and found the prisoner in custody of the crew. I took him, but only found a small piece of money on him - he had no hat on; I asked him where it was, one of the ship's company took up a hat from the deck, and said "Here is a hat;" the prisoner at first said it was his; but I looked into it, and found this watch - then he said it was not his. I put it on his head, and said "It is your's no doubt." I took him in the police-boat, and asked where he got the hat; he said he bought it on shore for 1 s. 6 d. I then said "Where did you get the watch?" he said I should hear about that next morning. I then called to the people on board the vessels in that tier, and said, if any person had lost a watch, they might apply to the office - the Times was one of the vessels. The prisoner then said, he had taken it from one of the vessels - he had only come out of prison on the Thursday, and he must go there again. I asked him how he found it in the dark; he said he heard the b - y thing tick, and took it through distress.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. I was three months in the House of Correction. I applied to the Prussian Consul, and he said "You have been in confinement, and shall go there again;" So I was obliged to go on board the ship, and take this watch to support me.</p>
